ðŸ”„ Parallel Streams in Java â€” a feature introduced in Java 8 that allows you to process collections concurrently with minimal code.

âš¡ 1. What are Parallel Streams?
A parallel stream divides the data into chunks, processes them in multiple threads, and merges the result â€” all without manual thread management.

It's built on ForkJoinPool.commonPool under the hood.

Syntax : list.parallelStream().forEach(item -> process(item));


âš ï¸ When to Use It
âœ… Use when:

Your data set is large
Each operation is CPU-bound
You donâ€™t need to maintain order

ðŸš« Avoid when:

Order of processing matters
Tasks are I/O bound or fast
Youâ€™re modifying shared state (mutable objects)

âš™ï¸ How It Works Internally

Uses ForkJoinPool.commonPool
Each stream operation is submitted as a task to be recursively split and joined
Uses spliterator to divide work

âœ… Summary (For Interview)

| Topic               | Details                                         |
| ------------------- | ----------------------------------------------- |
| `.parallelStream()` | Concurrent version of stream                    |
| ForkJoinPool        | Default executor behind parallel streams        |
| `forEachOrdered`    | Maintains order of original list                |
| When to use         | CPU-bound, large datasets, stateless operations |
| When to avoid       | Small datasets, I/O tasks, shared state         |


ðŸ”§ Customize Thread Pool (optional)

ForkJoinPool customPool = new ForkJoinPool(4);
customPool.submit(() ->
    list.parallelStream().forEach(item -> {
        // process
    })
).join();
